# arvo-graph — backlog

Deferred from the impl round that shipped the `BitMatrix64`-backed
algorithms. No design change needed to promote; only mechanical
duplication over the wider bitmask backing.

## BitMatrix256 variants

Every algorithm in arvo-graph (topo sort, renumber, upward/downward
rank, connected components, longest path, waist detection, spanning
tree) has a `BitMatrix64` form shipping now. The `BitMatrix256`
sibling, covering up to 256 nodes, shares the algorithmic shape —
only the `Mask64` → `Mask256` backing changes. Promote when a
consumer surfaces a concrete need for >64-node adjacency. Common
pipeline workloads per polka-dots research stay well under 64, so
this is a non-urgent widening.

Implementation note: the nested loops and the `[NodeId; N]` storage
stay the same; the `successors` / `predecessors` return type flips
from `Mask64` to `Mask256`, and the visited-set type follows. A
trait abstraction over the two matrix flavours could replace
duplication, but introducing one has its own const-expr cost on
current nightly — keep the two copies if promotion happens before
an ergonomic abstraction surfaces.
